AB  - Aircraft engine fault prediction plays a pivotal role in effective prognostic health management in the aerospace industry. Effective fault prognosis and management can enhance operational safety, reliability, and efficiency. While a lot of research has been dedicated to the data analytics and machine learning methods in predictive modeling, many of these models still lack transparency, operating as opaque "black boxes" without providing explanations for their predictions. The incorporation of a post-hoc explanation model can address this limitation and improve decision-making transparency, error analysis, and model verification. In this paper, we apply SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP), an explainability technique, to a convolutional neural network trained on a turbofan engine degradation dataset to predict failure. Through this approach, we learn and identify the most influential features in each prediction. This information empowers stakeholders and reliability engineers by providing insights into the critical engine components, settings, and sensors to focus on for remaining useful life monitoring and prolongation. © 2024 by the American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics, Inc. All rights reserved.
