AB  - In just a few years, LIME (Locally Interpretable Model-agnostic Explanations (Ribeiro et al., 2016)) has imposed itself as one of the key methods when it comes to post hoc interpretability machine learning models. This is in particular the case for deep neural networks. The exact operation of LIME, though, is often overlooked by practitioners, sometimes at great expense. One example in particular is the nature of the sampling process, which can lead to misleading explanations if not adapted to the data at hand. Another point is the role of LIME's hyperparameters, the provided explanations of which depend in a complicated manner. In this chapter, we summarize some recent theoretical work focused on LIME with the goal to propose some useful insights into the method. © 2023 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
